Using initial concentrations between 10 and 300 mg/L for both Cr(VI) and MO adsorbates, anionic pollutant concentrations are measured after equilibrium contact was achieved between the adsorbent and adsorbate (Fig. 7
                        ). The data obtained are then fitted using three of the previously mentioned isotherm models (Eqs. (8)–(10), SI). In Fig. 7, the adsorption isotherm plots (the Langmuir plotting Ce/qe vs Ce, Freundlich plotting ln(qe) vs ln(Ce), and Temkin plotting qe vs lnCe) for the three models are shown, and Table 3
                         contains fitting parameters. An outstanding correlation can be found between Langmuir's isotherm model and experimental data. The trend line and the Langmuir plot are almost entirely coincident with each other, as demonstrated by the Langmuir plot. In this regard, the Langmuir isotherm among the three isotherm models demonstrates a favorable match with the XG/CS/NCQDs hydrogel MO and Cr(VI) adsorption processes. In support of this, there are high correlation coefficients (R2 = 0.9993 and 0.9996), a Langmuir's constant above zero (kL > 0), and an appropriate separation factor (0 < RL < 1). Aside from the Langmuir model having higher correlation coefficients (R2) than the Freundlich and Temkin models (Table 3), Langmuir's model also predicts the qmax values that closely match those obtained experimentally for the adsorption of MO dye and Cr(VI) ions onto the XG/CS/NCQDs nanocomposite hydrogel. In regards to Cr(VI) ions, the maximum adsorption capacity was 291 mg/g, whereas for MO dye, it was 456 mg/g. Taking these results into account, it can be inferred that both anionic pollutants adsorb at the XG/CS/NCQDs surface with a uniform distribution of energetically equivalent active sites. The 1/n values (i.e., the inverse of the heterogeneity factor) <1.0 in the Freundlich model add further evidence that the XG/CS/NCQDs works well as an adsorption system for MO dye and Cr(VI) ions at all concentrations of the pollutants tested. Based on the Temkin adsorption isotherm, higher temperatures resulted in a higher value of B value, providing further supporting evidence for an increase in adsorption capacity as temperatures rise. According to the Langmuir model, Cr(VI) and MO can be adsorbed to XG/CS/NCQDs at Qmax values of 291 and 456 mg.g−1, respectively (Table 3), both of which are superior compared to previous reports for CS-based adsorbents (Table 4
                        ). This suggested that the XG/CS/NCQDs is potentially suitable for use as an adsorbent to remove various organic and inorganic pollutants contained in wastewater.
